 To find the longest palindromic substring in a given string in Java, you can use a combination of recursion and dynamic programming. Here's an implementation of the Manacher's algorithm, which is an efficient solution for this problem:

```java
public String longestPalindromeSubstring(String s) {
    if (s == null || s.length() < 1) return "";

    int start = 0, end = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < s.length(); i++) {
        int len1 = expandAroundCenter(s, i, i);
        int len2 = expandAroundCenter(s, i, i + 1);
        int maxLen = Math.max(len1, len2);

        if (maxLen > end - start) {
            start = i - (end - start) / 2;
            end = i;
        }
    }

    return s.substring(start, end + 1);
}

private int expandAroundCenter(String s, int left, int right) {
    while (left >= 0 && right < s.length() && s.charAt(left) == s.charAt(right)) {
        left--;
        right++;
    }

    return right - left - 1;
}
```

This implementation uses two helper functions: `expandAroundCenter` and `longestPalindromeSubstring`. The `expandAroundCenter` function expands a palindrome string around a center character. The `longestPalindromeSubstring` function uses this helper function to find the longest palindromic substring in the given string.

The time complexity of this solution is O(n), but it can be optimized to O(n) using a sliding window approach. However, the Manacher's algorithm is already quite efficient and should perform well for most inputs.

